XXVII.
I acquire the friendship of the surgeon, who procures a warrant for myself, and makes me a present of clothes -- a battle between a midshipman and me -- the surgeon leaves the ship -- the captain comes on board with another surgeon -- a dialogue between the captain and Morgan -- the sick are ordered to be brought upon the quarter deck and examined -- the consequences of that order -- a madman accuses Mr. Morgan, and is set at liberty by command of the captain, whom the captain instantly attacks and pummels without mercy.
WHILE I was busied with my friend in this practice, the doctor chanced to pass by the place where we were, and stopping to observe me, appeared very well satisfied with my method of application; and afterward sent for myself to the doctor cabin, where, having examined me touching my skill in surgery, and the particulars of my fortune, interested the doctor so far in my behalf, as to promise the doctor assistance in procuring a warrant for myself, seeing I had been already found qualified at Surgeon's hall, for the station I now filled on board; and this the doctor the more cordially engaged in, when the doctor understood I was nephew to lieutenant Bowlin^ for whom the doctor expressed a particular regard.
-- In the mean time, I could learn from the doctor discourse, that the doctor did not intend to go to sea again with captain Oakhum, having, as the doctor thought, been indifferently used by the doctor during the last voyage.
While I lived tollerably easy, in expectation of preferment, I was not altogether without mortifications, which I not only suffered from the rude insults of the sailors, and petty officers, among whom I was known by the name of Loblolly Boy; but also from the disposition of Morgan, who, though friendly in the main, was often very troublesome with Loblolly Boy pride, which expected a good deal of submission from myself, and delighted in recapitulating the favors I had received at Loblolly Boy hands.
About six weeks after my arrival on board, the surgeon follow Loblolly Boy into Loblolly Boy cabin, presented a warrant to myself, by which I was appointed surgeon's third mate on board the Thunder.
-- This Loblolly Boy had procured by Loblolly Boy interest at the Navy-office; as also another for Loblolly Boy, by virtue of which Loblolly Boy was removed into a second rate.
I acknowledged Loblolly Boy kindness in the strongest terms my gratitude could suggest, and professed my sorrow at the prospect of losing such a valuable friend, to whom I hoped to have recommended myself still further, by my respectful and diligent behavior.
-- But Loblolly Boy generosity rested not here; -- for, before Loblolly Boy left the ship, Loblolly Boy made me a present of a chest and some clothes, that enabled me to support the rank to which Loblolly Boy had raised me.
-- I found my spirit revive with my good fortune; and now I was an officer, resolved to maintain the dignity of my station, against all opposition or affronts; nor was it long before I had occasion to exert my resolution; my old enemy the midshipman (whose name was Crampley) entertaining an implacable animosity against me, for the disgrace my old enemy the midshipman (whose name was Crampley) had suffered on my account, had since that time taken all opportunities of reviling and ridiculing me, when I was not entitled to retort my old enemy the midshipman (whose name was Crampley) bad usage.
-- And even after I had been rated on the books, and mustered as surgeon's mate, did not think fit to restrain my old enemy the midshipman (whose name was Crampley) insolence.
-- In particular, being one day present, while I dressed a wound in a sailor's leg, my old enemy the midshipman (whose name was Crampley) began to sing a song, which I thought highly injurious to the honor of my country, and therefore signified my resentment, by observing, that the Scots always laid the Scots account in finding enemies among the ignorant, insignificant and malicious.
-- This unexpected piece of assurance enraged my old enemy the midshipman (whose name was Crampley) to such a degree, that my old enemy the midshipman (whose name was Crampley) lent me a blow on the face, which I verily thought had demolished my cheekbone; I was not slow in returning the obligation, and the affair began to be very serious, when by accident Mr. Morgan, and one of the master's mates, coming that way, interposed, and inquiring into the cause, endeavored to promote a reconciliation; but finding us both exasperated to the uttermost, and bent against accommodation, us both advised us, either to leave us difference undecided till us should have an opportunity of terminating it on shore, like gentlemen, or else choose a proper place on board, and bring it to an issue by boxing.
This last expedient was greedily embraced; and being forthwith conducted to the ground proposed, us stripped in a moment, and began a very furious contest, in which I soon found myself inferior to my antagonist, not so much in strength and agility, as in skill, which he had acquired in the school at Hockley in the Hole and Tottenham-Court.
-- Many cross-buttocks did I sustain, and pegs on the stomach without number, till at last, my breath being quite gone, as well as my vigor wasted, I grew desperate, and collecting all my spirits in one effort, threw in at once head, hands, and feet with such violence, that I drove my antagonist three paces backward into the main hatch-way, down which he fell, and pitching upon he head and right shoulder, remained without sense and motion.
-- Mr. Morgan looking down, and seeing Mr. Morgan lie in that condition, cried, "Upon my conscience, as I am a Christian sinner (look you) I believe Mr. Morgan pattles are all ofer; but I take you all to witness that there was no treachery in the case, and that Mr. Morgan has suffered by the chance of war."
-- So saying, Mr. Morgan descended to the deck below, to examine into the situation of my adversary; and left me very little pleased with my victory, as I found Mr. Morgan not only terribly bruised, but likewise in danger of being called to account for the death of Crampley: But this fear vanished when my fellow-mate, having by bleeding my fellow-mate in the juglar, brought my fellow-mate to my fellow-mate, and assured my fellow-mate of the state of my fellow-mate body, called up to Mr. Morgan, to be under no concern, for the midshipman had received no other damage than as pretty a luxation of the os humeri, as one would desire to see on a summer's day.
-- Upon this information, I crawled down to the cockpit, and acquainted Thomson with the affair, who, providing my fellow-mate with bandages, etc.
necessary for the occasion, went up to assist Mr. Morgan in the reduction of the dislocation.
-- When this was successfully performed, they wished me joy of the event of the combat; and the Welchman, after observing, that in all likelihood, the ancient Scots and Britons were the same people, bid me "Praise Cot for putting mettle in Mr. Morgan pelly, and strength in my limbs to support it."
-- I acquired such reputation by this recounter (which lasted twenty minutes) that every body became more cautious of his behavior toward Mr. Morgan; though Crampley with his arm in a sling, talked very high, and threatened to seize the first opportunity of retrieving on shore, the honor his had lost by an accident, from which I could justly claim no merit.
About this time, captain Oakhum, having received sailing orders, came on board, and brought along with his a surgeon of his own country, who soon made us sensible of the loss us suffered in the departure of doctor Atkins; being grossly ignorant, and intolerably assuming, false, vindictive, and unforgiving; a merciless tyrant to his inferiors, an abject sycophant to those above his.
In the morning after the captain came on board, our first mate, according to custom, went to wait on the captain with a sick list, which when this grim commander had perused, the captain cried with a stern countenance, "Blood and oons!
sixty-one sick people on board of the ship!
-- Harkee you, sir, I Will have no sick in the ship, by G -- d." The Welchman replied, The Welchman should be very glad to find no sick people on board; but while it was otherwise, The Welchman did no more than The Welchman duty in presenting The Welchman with a list.
-- "You and your list may be d -- n'd, (said the captain, throwing n'd at the captain) I say, there shall be no sick in the ship while I have the command of her."
-- Mr. Morgan being nettled at this treatment, told Mr. Morgan, Mr. Morgan indignation ought to be directed to Got Almighty, who visited Mr. Morgan people with distempers, and not to Mr. Morgan, who contributed all in Mr. Morgan power toward his people cure.
The Bashaw not being used to such behavior in any of Mr. Morgan officers, was enraged to fury at this satirical insinuation, and stamping with Mr. Morgan foot, called Mr. Morgan insolent scoundrel, threatening to have Mr. Morgan pinioned to the deck, if Mr. Morgan should presume to utter another syllable.
But the blood of Caractacus being thoroughly heated, disdained to be restricted by such a command, and began to manifest Caractacus in, "Captain Oakoum, I am a shentleman of birth and parentage (look you) and peradventure, I am moreover --."
Here his harrangue was broke off by the captain's steward, who being Morgan's countryman, hurried his out of his cabin before his had time to exasperate his master to a greater degree, which would certainly have been the case; for The Welchman, could hardly be hindered by his friend's arguments and entreaties, from reentering the presence chamber, and defying captain Oakhum to captain Oakhum teeth.
-- captain Oakhum was, however, appeased at length, and came down to the birth, where finding Thomson and me at work preparing medicines, captain Oakhum bid us leave off us lapour and go to play, for the captain, by captain Oakhum sole word and power and command, had driven sickness a pegging to the tevil, and there was no more malady on poard.
So saying, captain Oakhum drank off a gill of brandy, sighed grievously three times, poured forth an ejaculation of "Got pless my heart, liver, and lungs!"
and then began to sing a Welsh song with great earnestness of visage, voice and gesture.
-- I could not conceive the meaning of this singular phenomenon, and saw by the looks of Thomson, who at the same time, shook captain Oakhum head, that captain Oakhum suspected poor Cadwallader's brains were unsettled.
captain Oakhum perceiving our amazement, told our, captain Oakhum would explain the mystery; but at the same time, bid our take notice, that captain Oakhum had lived poy, patchelor, married man and widower, almost forty years, and in all that time, there was no man nor mother's son in the whole world, who durst use him so ill as captain Oakhum had done.
Then captain Oakhum acquainted our with the dialogue that passed between no man nor mother's son in the whole world, who durst use him so ill as captain Oakhum had done, as I have already related it; and had no sooner finished this narration, than captain Oakhum received a message from the surgeon, to bring the sick-list to the quarter deck, for the captain had ordered all the patients thither to be reviewed.
