-- When our appeared upon deck, the captain bid the doctor, who stood bowing at the captain right hand, look at these lazy, lubberly sons of bitches, who were good for nothing on board, but to eat the king's provision, and encourage idleness in the skulkers.
-- the surgeon grinned approbation, and taking the sick-list, began to examine the complaints of each as they could crawl to the place appointed.
-- The first who came under his cognizance, was a poor fellow just freed of a fever, which had weakened his so much, that his could hardly stand.
-- Mr. Mackshane (for that was the doctor's name) having felt his pulse, protested his was as well as any man in the world; and the captain delivered his over to the boatswain's mate, with orders that his should receive a round dozen at the gangway immediately, for counterfeiting his sick when his was not; -- but before the discipline could be executed, his dropped down on the quarter deck, and had well nigh perished under the hands of the executioner.
-- The next patient to be considered, labored under a quartan ague, and being then, in his interval of health, discovered no other symptoms of distemper, than a pale meagre countenance, and emaciated body; upon which, his was declared fit for duty, and turned over to the boatswain; -- but being resolved to disgrace the doctor, died upon the forecastle next day, during his cold fit.
-- The third complained of a pleuretic stitch, and spitting of blood, for which doctor Mackshane prescribed exercise at the pump to promote expectoration; but whether this was improper for one in his situation, or that it was used to excess, I know not, but in less than half an hour, his was suffocated with a deluge of blood that issued from his lungs.
-- A fourth, with much difficulty climbed to the quarter deck, being loaded with a monstrous ascites or dropsy, that invaded his chest so much, his could scarce fetch his breath; but his disease being interpreted into fat, occasioned by idleness and excess of eating, his was ordered, with a view to promote perspiration and enlarge his chest, to go aloft immediately: It was in vain for this unwieldy wretch, to allege his utter incapacity, the boatswain's driver was commanded to whip his up with a cat and nine tails: The smart of this application made his exert his so much, that his actually arrived at the foot-hook-shrouds, but when the enormous weight of his had nothing else to support his body than his weakened arms, either out of spite or necessity, his quitted his hold, and plumped into the sea, where his must have been drowned, had not a sailor who was in a boat along-side, saved his life, by keeping his afloat, till his was hoisted on board by a tackle -- It would be tedious and disagreeable to describe the fate of every miserable object that suffered by the inhumanity and ignorance of the captain and surgeon, who so wantonly sacrificed the lives of their fellow creatures.
Many were brought up in the height of fevers, and rendered delirious by the injuries they suffered in the way.
-- Some gave up the ghost in the presence of Some inspectors; and others, who were ordered to Some duty, languished a few days at work, among Some fellows, and then departed without any ceremony.
-- On the whole, the number of sick was reduced to less than a dozen; and the authors of this reduction were applauding Some for the service Some had done to Some king and country, when the boatswain's mate informed the boatswain's mate honor, that there was a man below lashed to the boatswain's mate hammock by the direction of the doctor's mate, and that the boatswain's mate begged hard to be released; affirming, the boatswain's mate had been so maltreated only for a grudge Mr. Morgan bore to the boatswain's mate, and that the boatswain's mate was as much in the boatswain's mate senses as any man aboard.
-- the captain hearing this, darted a severe look at The Welchman, and ordered his to be brought up immediately: Upon which, Mr. Morgan protested with great fervency, that the person in question was as mad as a March-hare; and begged for the the love of Got, Some would at least keep his arms pinioned during his examination, to prevent his from doing mischief.
-- This request this grim commander granted for this grim commander own sake, and the patient was produced, who insisted upon this grim commander being in this grim commander right wits with such calmness and strength of argument, that every body present was inclined to believe this grim commander, except Morgan, who affirmed there was no trusting to appearances; for this grim commander had been so much imposed upon by this grim commander behavior two days before, that this grim commander had actually unbound this grim commander with this grim commander own hands, and had well nigh been murdered for this grim commander pains: this was confirmed by the evidence of one of the waiters, who declared, this grim commander had pulled this patient from the doctor's mate, whom this grim commander had gotten down and almost strangled.
-- To this his answered, that the witness was a creature of Mr. Morgan's, and was suborned to give his testimony against his by the malice of the mate, whom the defendant had affronted, by discovering to the people on board, that Mr. Morgan's wife kept a gin-shop in Rag-Fair.
-- This anecdote produced a laugh at the expense of the Welchman, who shaking his head with some emotion, said, "Ay, ay, it is no matter.
-- Got knows, it is an arrant falsehood."
-- Captain Oakhum, without any further hesitation, ordered the fellow to be unfettered; at the same time, threatening to make Mr. Morgan exchange situations with the fellow for the fellow spite; but the Briton no sooner heard the decision in favor of the madman, than the fellow got up the mizzen-shrouds, crying to Thomson and me to get out of the fellow reach, for Thomson and me should see the fellow play the tevil with a vengeance.
Thomson and me did not think fit to disregard this caution, and accordingly got up on the poop, whence Thomson and me beheld the maniac (as soon as the fellow was released) fly at the captain like a fury, crying, "I Will let you know, you scoundrel, that I am commander of this vessel" -- and pummel the captain without mercy.
The surgeon, who went to the assistance of the captain patron, shared the same fate; and it was with the utmost difficulty, that the captain was mastered at last, after having done great execution among those who opposed the captain.
