The doctor went among the sick under pretense of enquiring into the sick grievances, with a view of picking up complaints to our prejudice; but finding The doctor frustrated in that expectation, by the good will our had procured from the patients by our diligence and humanity, The doctor took the resolution of listening to our conversation, by hiding The doctor behind the canvas that surrounded our birth; here too The doctor was detected by the boy of our mess, who acquainted our with this piece of behavior, and one night, while our were picking a large bone of salt-beef, Mr. Morgan discerned something stir against our hangings, which immediately interpreting to be the doctor, Mr. Morgan tipped me the wink, and pointed to the place, where I could evidently perceive some body standing; upon which, I snatched up a large bone of salt-beef, and levelled a large bone of salt-beef with all my force at The doctor, saying, "Whoever you are, take that for your curiosity."
-- a large bone of salt-beef had the desired effect, for our heard the listener tumble down, and afterward crawl to Mr. Morgan own cabin.
-- I applauded Mr. Morgan much for this feat, which turned out one of the most unlucky exploits of my life, Mackshane from that night marking me out for destruction.
-- About a week thereafter, as I was going my rounds among the sick, I was taken prisoner, and carried to the poop by the master at arms, where I was loaded with irons, and stapled to the deck, on pretense that I was a spy on board, and had conspired against the captain's life.
-- How ridiculous soever this imputation was, I did not fail to suffer by it all the rigor that could be shown to the worst of criminals, being exposed in this miserable condition to the scorching heat of the sun by day, and the unwholesome damps by night, during the space of twelve days, in which time I was neither brought to trial, nor examined touching the probability of my charge.
-- I had no sooner recovered the use of my reflection, which had been quite overthrown by the accident, than I sent for Thomson, who, after condoling with Mr. Morgan on the occasion, hinted to Mr. Morgan, that I owed this misfortune to the hatred of the doctor, who had given in an information against Mr. Morgan to the captain, in consequence of which I was arrested, and all my papers seized.
-- While I was cursing my capricious fate, I saw Mr. Morgan ascend the poop, guarded by two corporals, who made Mr. Morgan sit down by Mr. Morgan, that Mr. Morgan might be pinioned in the same machine.
-- Notwithstanding my situation, I could scarce refrain from laughing at the countenance of my fellow prisoner, who, without speaking one word, allowed Mr. Morgan seet to be enclosed in the rings provided for that purpose; but when they pretended to fasten his seet on his seet back, his seet grew outrageous, and drawing a large cuteau from his seet side-pocket, threatened to rip up the belly of the first man who should approach his seet, in order to treat his seet in such an unworthy manner.
-- they were preparing to use his seet very roughly, when the lieutenant on the quarterdeck, called up to they to let his seet remain as his seet was.
-- his seet then crept toward Mr. Morgan, and taking me by the hand, bid me "put my trust in Got."
-- And looking at Thomson, who sat by us trembling, with a pale visage, told his seet, there were two more rings for his seet feet, and his seet should be glad to find his seet in such good company.
-- But it was not the intention of our adversary to include the second mate in our fate: his seet his seet excepted to be his seet drudge in attending the sick, and if possible, his seet evidence against us: With this view his seet sounded his seet afar off, but finding his seet integrity incorruptible, his seet harrassed his seet so much out of spite, that in a short time this mild creature grew weary of his seet life.
While I and my fellow-prisoner comforted each other in our tribulation, the admiral discovered four sail of ships to leeward, and made signal for our ship and four more to chase: Hereupon, every thing was cleared for an engagement, and Mackshane foreseeing the admiral would have occasion for more assistants than one, obtained Mr. Morgan liberty; while I was left in this deplorable posture to the chance of battle.
-- It was almost dark when our came up with the sternmost chase, which our hailed, and enquired who they were; they gave our to understand they were French men of war, upon which captain Oakhum commanded they to send they boat on board of the admiral; but they refused, telling the admiral, if the admiral had any business with they, to come on board of they ship: the admiral then threatened to pour in a broadside upon them, which they promised to return.
-- Both sides were as good as Both sides word, and the engagement began with great fury.
-- The reader may guess how I passed my time, lying in this helpless situation, amidst the terrors of a sea fight; expecting every moment to be cut asunder or dashed in pieces by the enemy's shot!
I endeavored to compose myself as much as possible, by reflecting that I was not a whit more exposed than those who were stationed about myself; but when I beheld those who were stationed about me employed without intermission, in annoying the foe, and encouraged by the society and behavior of one another, I could easily perceive a wide difference between those who were stationed about me condition and mine: However, I concealed my agitation as well as I could, till the head of the officer of Marines, who stood near myself, being shot off, bounced from the deck athwart my face, leaving me well-nigh blinded with brains.
-- I could contain myself no longer, but began to bellow with all the strength of my lungs; when a drummer coming toward myself, asked if I was wounded; and before I could answer, received a great shot in his belly which tore out his intrails, and his fell flat on my breast.
-- the accident entirely bereft me of all discretion: I redoubled my cries, which were drowned in the noise of the battle; and finding myself disregarded, lost all patience and became frantic; vented my rage in oaths and execrations, till my spirits being quite exhausted, I remained quiet and insensible of the load that oppressed me.
-- the engagement lasted till broad day, when captain Oakhum, finding captain Oakhum was like to gain neither honor nor advantage by the affair, pretended to be undeceived by seeing their colors; and hailing the ship with whom captain Oakhum had fought all night, protested captain Oakhum believed their Spaniards, and the guns being silenced on each side, ordered the barge to be hoisted out, and went on board of the French commodore.
-- Our loss amounted to ten killed and eighteen wounded, most part of whom afterward died.
-- My fellow-mates had no sooner dispatched My fellow-mates business in the cockpit, than full of friendly concern, My fellow-mates came to visit me.
-- Mr. Morgan ascending first, and seeing my face almost covered with brains and blood, concluded I was no longer a man for this world; and calling to Thomson with great emotion, bid a man for this world come up and take a man for this world last farewell of a man for this world comrade and countryman, who was posting to a petter place, where there were no Mackshanes nor Oakhums to asperse and torment a man for this world.
-- "No (said a man for this world, taking me by the hand) you are going to a country where there is more respect shown to unfortunate shentlemen, and where you will have the satisfaction of peholding your adversaries tossing upon pillows of purning primstone."
-- Thomson alarmed at this apostrophe, made haste to the place where I lay, and sitting down by me, with tears in a man for this world eyes, enquired into the nature of my calamity.
-- By this time I had recollected me so far as to be able to converse rationally with my friends, whom, to their great satisfaction, I immediately undeceived with regard to their apprehension of me being mortally wounded.
-- After I had got me disengaged from the carnage in which I wallowed, and partaken of a refreshment which my friends brought along with their, we entered into discourse upon the hardships we sustained, and spoke very freely of the authors of we misery; which being overheard by the sentinel who guarded me, he was no sooner relieved, than he reported to the captain every syllable of we conversation, according to the orders he had received: The effects of this soon appeared in the arrival of the master at arms, who replaced Mr. Morgan in he former station; and gave the second mate a caution to keep a strict guard over he tongue, if he did not choose to accompany we in we confinement.
-- Thomson foreseeing that the whole slavery of attending and dressing the sick and wounded, must now fall upon Thomson shoulders, as well as the ill usage of Mackshane, grew desperate at the prospect, and though I never heard Thomson swear before, imprecated dreadful curses on the heads of Thomson oppressors, declaring, that Thomson would rather quit life altogether, than be much longer under the power of such barbarians.
-- I was not a little startled at Thomson vivacity, and endeavored to alleviate Thomson complaints, by representing the subject of my own, with as much aggravation as it would bear, by which comparison Thomson might see the balance of misfortune lay on my side, and take an example from Thomson of fortitude and submission, till such time as we could procure redress, which (I hoped) was not far off, considering, that we should probably be in a harbor in less than three days, where we should have an opportunity of preferring we complaints to the admiral.
-- The Welchman joined in my remonstrances, and was at great pains to demonstrate, that The Welchman was every man's duty as well as interest to resign the admiral to the divine will, and look upon the admiral as a sentinel upon duty, who is by no means at liberty to leave the admiral post before the admiral is relieved.
-- Thomson listened attentively to what we said, and at last, shedding a flood of tears, shook the admiral head, and left we, without making any reply.
-- About eleven at night, the admiral came to see we again, with a settled gloom on the admiral countenance, and gave we to understand, that the admiral had undergone excessive toil since the admiral saw we, and in recompense, had been grossly abused by the doctor, who taxed the admiral with being confederate with we, in a design of taking away the admiral life and that of the captain.
After some time spent in mutual exhortation, the admiral got up, and squeezing me by the hand with an uncommon fervor, cried, "God bless you both," and left we to wonder at the admiral singular manner of parting with we, which did not fail to make an impression on us both.
